## Fast installation

The signed installer downloads the GGUF file, verifies its SHA-256 checksum,
starts a loopback-only API, and adds Metaflora Incubus v1 to supported local
clients.

macOS and Linux:

```sh
curl -fsSL https://metaflora.ai/incubus/install | sh
```

Windows PowerShell:

```powershell
irm https://metaflora.ai/incubus/install.ps1 | iex
```

After installation, select `Metaflora Incubus v1` in OpenCode. The installer
manages the local endpoint and its client entry. No API key is required for the
loopback service.

## Ollama

Download `metaflora-incubus-v1-q4.gguf` and place it next to a file named
`Modelfile` with this content:

```dockerfile
FROM ./metaflora-incubus-v1-q4.gguf
PARAMETER num_ctx 8192
```

Create and run the local model:

```sh
ollama create metaflora-incubus:v1 -f Modelfile
ollama run metaflora-incubus:v1
```

The GGUF metadata carries the chat template. Do not add a different `TEMPLATE`
line unless a release note explicitly requires it.

## llama.cpp

Use a recent `llama-server` build with GGUF support:

```sh
llama-server \
  -m ./metaflora-incubus-v1-q4.gguf \
  --host 127.0.0.1 \
  --port 11435 \
  -c 8192
```

The server exposes an OpenAI-compatible API at
`http://127.0.0.1:11435/v1`.

## Any OpenAI-compatible client

Set the client fields to:

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| Base URL | `http://127.0.0.1:11435/v1` |
| API key | leave empty, or use `local` if the client requires a value |
| Model ID | `metaflora-incubus-v1` |
| Display name | `Metaflora Incubus v1` |

Test the endpoint directly:

```sh
curl http://127.0.0.1:11435/v1/chat/completions \
  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
  -d '{
    "model": "metaflora-incubus-v1",
    "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "Write a small HTTP server."}],
    "temperature": 0.2
  }'
```

Keep the service bound to `127.0.0.1`. Public network exposure requires
authentication, request limits, logging controls, and a separate security
review.

## Intended use

The model is built for:

- code generation, explanation, review, and repository edits;
- structured tool calls in compatible agent clients;
- search tasks where the client supplies a search tool and returns sources;
- Russian and English drafting, editing, summarisation, and analysis;
- private local inference on a single-user computer.

The model itself has no network access. Search, shell commands, file changes,
and other actions come from the client and its configured tools.

## Refusal behaviour

The local runtime adds no cloud moderation layer. Training and release tests aim
to reduce unjustified refusals on lawful, benign requests while keeping answers
useful and instruction-following. This does not guarantee that every prompt
receives an answer or that every answer is correct. The published release report
must include the size, categories, confidence interval, and raw anonymised
results of the refusal evaluation.

